(646,	'05786',	'5786 语态 - 被动\n\n    被动语态表示主词是接受动作者, 例:\"这男孩被球击中了\" ,\n    这男孩是接受动作的人.',	'5786 Voice - Passive\n\n The passive voice indicates that the subject is the receptive actor, for example: “The boy was hit by the ball”,\n This boy is the one who takes the action.',	1),
(647,	'05787',	'5787 语态 - 关身或被动\n\n    许多所谓的 \"deponent\" dep动词, 可以是关身或被动形式. \n    翻译时通常以主动形式表现, 因为它们没有主动语态的字形.\n    不过, 有时仍会按关身或被动来翻译它.',	'5787 Voice - Shut Down or Passive\n\n Many so-called “deponent” dep verbs, can be shut down or passive forms. \n They are usually expressed in active form when translated, because they do not have active voice glyphs.\n Nevertheless, it is still sometimes translated as closed or passive.',	1),
(648,	'05849',	'同义词\n\n   见 theiotes 的定义       2305\n   见 theotes  的定义       2320\n\n   2320 \"神性\"与 2305\"神性\"的不同在于存在的本质与属性之间的不同',	'synonyms\n\n See definition of theiotes 2305\n See definition of theotes 2320\n\n The difference between 2320 “divinity” and 2305 “divinity” lies in the difference between the nature and attributes of existence',	1),
(649,	'05776',	'5776 时态 - 未来式\n\n    希腊文的未来式相当于英文中的未来式, 表示一件预期或可能会发生的事,\n    不过现今尚未发生\n.',	'5776 Tense - Futuristic\n\n The Greek futuristic is equivalent to the futuristic in English and denotes an event that is expected or likely to happen,\n But it hasn\'t happened yet\n.',	1),
(650,	'05790',	'5790 语态 - 关身或被动形主动意\n\n    关身或被动形式主动意的动词(dep)几乎都以主动语态翻译.\n\n    见 \"主动\" # 5784',	'5790 Voice - Shut Down or Passively Active\n\n Virtually all verbs that take the initiative (dep) are translated in the active voice.\n\n See “Proactive” # 5784',	1),
(651,	'03242',	'3242 未曾使用过',	'3242 never used',	1),
(652,	'05774',	'5774 时态 - 现在式\n\n    希腊文的现在式表达一个简单的事实, 在某一个确定时间所发生的.\n    它通常相当于英文中的现在式. 然而, 它也常被译为过去式, 就是所谓的\n     \"历史上确实存在的一个状况\" , 也就是说读者好像在过去的那个时间\n    里, 亲眼目睹了事件发生的过程. 不过有时它仍被译为现在式.',	'5774 Tense - Present Tense\n\n The present expression in Greek expresses a simple fact, which happened at a certain time.\n It is usually equivalent to the present style in English. However, it is also often translated as the past tense, which is called\n “a situation that does exist in history”, which means that the reader seems to have been at that time in the past\n Ri, who witnessed the course of the incident. Sometimes, however, it is still translated as it is now.',	1),
