(6017,	'05330',	'5330 Pharisaios {far-is-ah\'-yos}\n\n源于希伯来字, 参 06567; TDNT - 9:11,1246; 阳性名词\n\n钦定本 - Pharisee 100; 100\n\n1) 一个犹太教派, 似乎发轫于犹太人被掳之后。除了旧约书卷之外,\n   法利赛人还认可口传的信仰与生活准则。表面上恪守礼仪, 诸如洁\n   净、禁食、祷告、周济, 藉此沽名钓誉; 以自以为是的好行为自豪\n   , 相对之下却忽略了敬虔实质。坚信有善恶天使, 也期待弥赛亚降\n   临; 所怀的盼望是, 死人在阴间先经过赏罚之后, 神使之复活, 再\n   按着个别的行为报应各人。与执政的罗马当局唱反调, 拥护神权政\n   治并家国利益, 对普罗大众有举足轻重的影响力。根据犹太史学家\n   约瑟夫的研究, 他们总共有六千多人; 对耶稣恨之入骨, 耶稣也痛\n   斥他们人心不足蛇吞象、野心勃勃、假冒为善。',	'5330 Pharisaios {far-is-ah\'-yos}\n\nDerived from the Hebrew word, 06567; TDNT - 9:11 ,1246; masculine noun\n\nConfinement Book - Pharisee 100; 100\n\n1) A Jewish sect that seems to have originated after the abduction of Jews. In addition to the books of the Old Testament,\n The Pharisees also recognized oral beliefs and guidelines for life. Observe manners on the surface, such as cleanliness\n Net, fasting, prayer, and Zhou Ji, to sell fame; take pride in self-righteous good behavior\n In contrast, the essence of piety is ignored. I firmly believe that there are angels of good and evil, and I also expect the Messiah to come\n P; the hope is that after the dead have been rewarded and punished in the underworld, God resurrected them, and then\n Reward everyone according to their individual actions. Sing antagonism with the ruling Roman authorities and advocating theocracy\n Ruling and merging the interests of the country will have an important influence on the general public. According to Jewish historians\n Joseph\'s research, they totaled more than 6,000 people; they hate Jesus, and Jesus hurts too\n Rebuke them for not being enough to swallow snakes, be ambitious, and fake for good.',	1),
(6018,	'00749',	'749 archiereus {ar-khee-er-yuce\'}\n\n源于 746 和 2409; TDNT - 3:265,349; 阳性名词\n\nAV - chief priest 64, high priest 58, chief of the priest 1; 123\n\n1) 祭司长, 大祭司\n在祭司中最大的一, 即祭司长. 他也有权行一般祭司的职分, 但其最主要的任务是在每年一度的赎罪日\n时, 进入至圣所(这是其他祭司所不能进入的地方)为他自己和其他所有人的罪献祭, 并在商议宗教上的\n审判事件时主持犹太人的最高评议会(即公会). 根据摩西的律法, 只有亚伦的子孙中曾任大祭司的人的\n后裔才可以担任大祭司的职分, 而且其大祭司的身分是终身的. 但自从安提阿哥以比芬尼起, 西流基诸\n王和其后希律家族的统治者及罗马人开始干涉大祭司的任命权, 这职分即不保证授与宗教领袖的家族,\n也不再是终身的; 它变成是可以用捐钱购买的, 而且是随民政或军事长官的喜好而可任意任命的. \n在大希律统治到圣城被毁的一百零七年间, 共有廿八个人曾拥有此宗教领袖的身分.\n\n2) 大祭司们(或公会中的领袖), 除了任祭司长职分的那位外, 也包括所有曾任祭司长的人和虽然已经\n去职, 但在这职分上仍具有相当权力的人, 甚至包括那些大祭司家族中对公众有相当影响力的人.\n\n3) 用以指基督, 因其献上自己, 流血作了对神的赎罪祭, 而且已经进入天上的圣所作我们的中保',	'749 archiereus {ar-khee-er-yuce\'}\n\nDerived from 746 and 2409; TDNT - 3:265 ,349; positive noun\n\nAV - Chief of the Chief 64, High Chief 58, Chief of the Chief 1; 123\n\n1) Chief Priest, High Priest\nThe biggest one among the priests, is the chief priest. He also has the right to perform the duties of an ordinary priest, but his main task is on the annual Yom Kippur\nfrom time to time, enter the Most Sanctuary (a place where no other priest can enter) to sacrifice for his own sins and for all others, and to negotiate religious\nPresides over the highest council (ie the guild) of the Jews at the trial of events. According to the law of Moses, only those of Aaron\'s children who were once high priests\nDescendants can only assume the rank of high priest, and their status as high priest is lifelong. But since Antiago began with Bifeni, Xiliu Kijo\nThe king and later rulers of the Herod family and the Romans began to interfere with the appointment of high priests, which did not guarantee the family conferred on religious leaders,\nIt is no longer permanent; it can be purchased with donated money and can be appointed arbitrarily as the civilian or military chief prefers. \nFrom the time of the reign of Herod the Great and the destruction of the Holy City in 2007, a total of 28 people had the status of leader of this religion.\n\n2) The high priests (or leaders of the guild), in addition to the one who held the rank of chief priest, also included all those who had been priests and those who had\nThose who went out of office, but still had considerable power in this post, even those in the high priestly family who had considerable influence over the public.\n\n3) It is used to refer to Christ, who sacrificed himself, bled to make an atonement sacrifice to God, and has entered our sanctity in heaven',	1),
